<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0132</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0132.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   Contra Correction</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><RE>CENTRAL AMERICA (CME)NICARAGUA (NU)</RE><LP>   Before their 1990 defeat at the polls, the Sandinistas'chief propagandist in the U.S. was a foreign-ministryofficial named Alejandro Bendana. The most dominant theme,which he repeated over and over on U.S. TV, was that theContras were CIA-funded thugs who didn't represent thepeople. Hollywood celebrities, church officials and more thana few Congressmen soulfully agreed. Now, in &quot;A CampesinoTragedy: Testimonies of the Resistance,&quot; Mr. Bendana correctsthe record: &quot;The contra army grew beyond the North Americans'own expectations, not as a result of sophisticatedrecruitment campaigns in the countryside but primarilybecause of the impact on the campesino parcelero of theSandinistas' policies, limitations and errors.&quot;</LP><TEXT/></DOC>